**When in doubt whether a skill applies:** invoke the `workflow-coach` agent with the user's request before doing anything. It reads the workflow docs and skill definitions and will identify the right skill â€” or confirm none applies. Only invent a custom process after `workflow-coach` confirms no skill covers the situation.

## Multi-Task Sessions

When the user gives multiple tasks in one message (e.g. "refine FEAT-001, FEAT-002, then implement both"):

**1. Checkpoint immediately â€” before any work:**
Write the full task list to the branch-scoped context file (`.claude/memory/context-{branch}.md`) under `## In Progress`:
```markdown
## In Progress
task: Multi-task session â€” {brief description}
tasks:
- [ ] Refine FEAT-001
- [ ] Refine FEAT-002
- [ ] Implement FEAT-001
- [ ] Implement FEAT-002
next_step: "Refine FEAT-001"
saved_at: {timestamp}
```

**2. Work through in order:**
Invoke the relevant skill for each item. After each completes, tick it off (`- [x]`) and update `next_step`, then immediately start the next item.

- **Supervised mode**: each skill runs normally â€” ask all the questions it normally asks. The only difference from a normal session is that after a skill finishes, move on to the next task automatically instead of stopping. Do not add extra confirmation prompts *between* tasks ("should I continue with the next item?") â€” just continue.
- **Unsupervised mode**: all skills apply their autonomous defaults (no questions). Proceed fully automatically.

**3. Compact between phases (user action â€” do not self-invoke):**
`/compact` is a built-in Claude Code command that only the **user** can trigger â€” it cannot be reliably self-invoked across CLI, VS Code, or web environments. Do NOT call it yourself.

Instead, at a phase boundary (e.g. all refines done, about to start implementations):
- Ensure all changes are committed and the checkpoint is fully up to date
- In supervised mode: ask the user "Context is getting large â€” please run `/compact` so I can continue cleanly." Wait for confirmation, then continue.
- In unsupervised mode: skip the compact, continue directly. The infrastructure will compress context automatically when needed.

After the user runs `/compact`: immediately read `.claude/memory/context-{branch}.md` to restore the task list, then continue with the next unchecked item.

**4. Done only when every item is checked off:**
Clear `## In Progress` only after all items show `[x]`. The Stop hook will remind you of remaining work if you try to stop early.

## Session Behavior

If the session start context contains `=== AUTO-RESUME REQUIRED ===`, immediately execute `/resume` without waiting for user input.

If the session start context contains `=== IN-PROGRESS WORK FOUND ===`, tell the user what task is in progress and suggest they run `/resume` to continue â€” but do not resume automatically.

If a hook reports `SUPERVISED_USAGE_ALERT`: use `AskUserQuestion` to ask the user whether they want to switch to unsupervised mode now (so auto-resume becomes available). Options: yes at 80% / yes with a custom threshold / no. If they agree, run `/unsupervised on [threshold]`; if not, continue normally. The alert will not repeat until usage drops and rises again.

If `.claude/memory/settings.md` contains `unsupervised: true`:
- **Never** use `AskUserQuestion` â€” apply autonomous defaults from the `/unsupervised` skill
- If a hook reports `USAGE THRESHOLD REACHED`: commit the current atomic step, update the checkpoint, then pick one:
  - **`.claude/memory/loop-mode.marker` present** (running under `claude-loop.sh`): stop the session â€” the loop will restart it with a fresh context window and resume from the checkpoint automatically.
  - **A schedule-a-future-message tool is available** (e.g. `send_later`, `ScheduleWakeup` â€” cloud/remote session, no attached terminal): run `bash .claude/hooks/usage-guard.sh --check` once; if not `RESUME_OK`, schedule a wakeup 20â€“30 minutes out and end the turn instead of polling with Bash sleeps â€” repeat on each wakeup until `RESUME_OK`. Do not use `--wait` here.
  - **Neither applies** (interactive VS Code / terminal session): run `bash .claude/hooks/usage-guard.sh --wait` (3-minute Bash timeout) repeatedly until it prints `RESUME_OK`, then continue working.
- If you hit a genuine blocker (merge conflict, missing credentials, unresolvable ambiguity), write `## Blocked: <reason>` to `.claude/memory/context.md` and stop â€” do not wait for input
- When all work is complete, clear `## In Progress` from `.claude/memory/context.md` and stop

## Memory

`.claude/memory/` contains project memory (decisions, context, gotchas, tech-debt). Read these when they are relevant â€” they are not auto-loaded.

**Multi-session checkpoint isolation:** Context is stored per branch to avoid conflicts when multiple Claude Code sessions work on the same repository simultaneously. Always use `.claude/memory/context-{branch}.md` as the checkpoint file, where `{branch}` = current git branch with `/` replaced by `-` (e.g. `feature/feat-001-login` â†’ `context-feature-feat-001-login.md`). Determine it at runtime: `git branch --show-current | sed 's|/|-|g'`. When reading context, try the branch-scoped file first; fall back to `context.md` only for legacy checkpoints.

## Context Management

Compress the conversation proactively to avoid token exhaustion mid-task. Long sessions accumulate context fast â€” a single `/implement` run for a non-trivial feature can approach the limit.

**Compact after every natural boundary:**
- After each subtask's commit during `/implement` (right before starting the next subtask)
- After a `/pr` review-and-fix cycle completes
- After `/refine` finishes and the spec is ready
- Whenever the conversation exceeds ~40 messages or starts feeling sluggish

**Before every compact, ensure all state is on disk:**
1. All in-progress changes are committed and pushed
2. `.claude/memory/context.md` reflects the current task ID, branch, and next step
3. Spec checkboxes match actual progress (they are the subtask source of truth)

**How to compact:** run `/compact` in Claude Code. The harness summarizes the conversation; the summary plus the memory files give full orientation for the next burst of work.

**After compacting:** read `.claude/memory/context.md` before continuing so you pick up exactly where the work left off.

**Safe vs. unsafe compact windows:**
- **Safe**: immediately after a successful commit + checkpoint update â€” everything is persisted
- **Unsafe**: mid-subtask with uncommitted edits, or while waiting for a tool result â€” finish the atomic unit first
